    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Genre scenes that depict soldiers drinking, resting, and gambling. Coortegardjes enjoyed their greatest popularity during the 1620s and 1630s, perhaps as a result of Dutch preoccupation with the ongoing war with Spain.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046913/Albany Institute of History and Art [online] (n.d.)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Een genrestuk met een afbeelding van drinkende, rustende en gokkende soldaten in hun wachtlokalen. Kortegaarden waren vooral populair tijdens de jaren 20 en 30 van de 17de eeuw, wellicht een gevolg van de aanhoudende oorlog met Spanje.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000104484/Rijksmuseum [online] (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
